  1. The following 5 date columns: ListingCreationDate, ClosedDate, DateCreditPulled, FirstRecordedCreditLine, LoanOriginationDate are of incorrect data types.
  2. ListingNumber, LoanNumber are Key/ID columns classified as float/int(no claculation will be perfomed on these).
  3. Several categorical columns classified as "objects".
  4. The dataset contains attributes on 3 objects, Listing, Loan and Borrower details. However we will select specific columns that will be of interest for our investigation.

def convertOccupation(name):
    try:
        return name.split('-')[0]
    except AttributeError as error:
        return name
In [14]:
loanDataSubset["Occupation"] = loanDataSubset["Occupation"].apply(convertOccupation)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset comprises data on 113937 loans with 81 attributes corresponding to the loan, borrower and lender's details. 61 columns are numeric including the key/id columns and categorical types for ListingCategory. The columns include, amoung others; BorrowerRate, EmploymentStatus, IncomeRange, LoanOriginalAmount.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in features that determain a loans outcome status?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I suspect a borrower's ability to pay back a loan is greatly affected by their "DebtToIncomeRatio", the lower the ratio, the more finance available to repay a loan. I suspect other variables associated with debt and income, though not to as much an extent, will also affect the borrower's ability to repay. Attributes like BorrowerAPR, ListingCategory, EmploymentStatus and IncomeRange

Univariate Exploration¶

We start by looking at the distribution of the outcome variable: LoanStatus.

In [25]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
order = loanDataSubset['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index
sb.countplot(data=loanDataSubset, x='LoanStatus', color=base_color, order=order)
plt.title("Distribution of LoanStatus")
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

It appears the majority of the Loans are current, with fewer and fewer loans as the days past due increase. It would be interesting to see how this relates to loan duration. Is this because most loans span over a the 9 year period covered by this data?

In [26]:
# Use the same pokemon dataset
sorted_counts = loanDataSubset['Term'].value_counts()
plt.pie(sorted_counts, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle = 90, counterclock = False)
plt.legend(title='Term Length', labels = ['3yrs', '5yrs', '1yr'])
plt.title("Count of Loans by Term length")
plt.axis('square');

It appears loans in this dataset have a term length of 1, 3 and 5years. It is amaizing how dispite the dataset spanning twice the period of the longest term loan, Current loans has the highest freaquency. It must be loan listing is increasing each year.

In [27]:
def date_to_year(datetime_object):
    return datetime_object.year
In [28]:
#Create a columns with start year for each loan
loanDataSubset['LoanComencementYear'] = loanDataSubset['LoanOriginationDate'].apply(date_to_year)
In [29]:
sb.countplot(data=loanDataSubset, x='LoanComencementYear', color=base_color)
plt.title("Count of Loans by Year of Origin");

As suspected, there is an upward trend in the data. The first before 2008, and a sharp drop for 2009, consistanmt with the global depression of 2008, and the second upward trend from 2009 going forward. The trend for 2005 and 2014 is consistant as there are only 2 and 3 months for the respectives years in the dataset. The majority of the loans originated in the last 3 years of the dataset, with 2013 having the highest count and 2012 in second place.

In [64]:
def income_distribution(binsize):
    bins = np.arange(loanDataSubset['StatedMonthlyIncome'].min(), loanDataSubset['StatedMonthlyIncome'].max()+binsize, binsize)
    plt.hist(data=loanDataSubset, x="StatedMonthlyIncome", bins=bins)
    locs, ticks = plt.xticks()
    plt.title('Distribution of StatedMonthlyIncome')
    plt.xlabel('StatedMonthlyIncome ($)')
    plt.xticks(locs, ['','$0', "250k", '500k', '750k', '1M', '1.25M', '1.5M', '1.75M', '2M'])

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The variable of interest is LoanStatus. The majority of the loans are distributed between Current and Completed loans, with "Current" having the highest count for period in question than any other category. With the except of Loans between 16-30 days past due, it appears as the days "Past Due" increase, the count of loans increase. There are very few loans that were canceled, with loans in the "FinalPaymentInProgress" having the third lowest count.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution for StatedMonthlyIncome appeared unusual, with all point clustured about \$0. This was because of outliers, with the highest at about \$1,750,000 from the previous point at around \$500,000. The data was retained as it is consistant with the provided income ranges.

LoanStatus, IncomeRange and EmploymentStatus datatype was changed to "Categorical" and LoanOriginationDate was converted to a datetime object. An additional column was created so as to group loans by "LoanOriginationYear".

The following finding we established:

  1. Term - The loans were disbursed with only 3 term duration, 1 , 3 and 5 years. 77% of the loans were of a 5 year length.
  2. LoanComencementYear - There is an implicity relationship between LoanComencementYear and LoanStatus, with the highest count of loan having originated in 2013.
  3. IncomeRange - the highest frequence of salaries is between "25k&50k" with the second highest between "50k&75k".
  4. StatedMonthlyIncome - 75% of the salaries lie below \$6,825.
  5. BorrowerAPR - The majority of the data lie between 0.05 and 0.4, with a few points before 0.05 and between 0.4 and 0.5.
  6. The most popular list category is category 1:Debt Consolidation.

The highest correlation is between LoanOriginalAmount and MonthltLoanPayments, the bigger the loan the higher the monthly payments for the same term length. The is also a positive correlation of 0.2 between LoanOriginalAmount and StatedMonthlyIncome which translates to the higher the income, the higher the loan one gets.

DebtToIncomeRatio and StatedMonthlyIncome are negatively ocrrelated, i.e the higher your income, the higher your chances of paying back the debt. Also BorrowerAPR is negatively correlated to LoanOriginalAmount and MonthltLoanPayments. This makes sence since BorrowerAPR is a ratio of LoanOriginalAmount, the higher the denominator, the lower the ratio.

The majority of the loans listed were of below \$15,000 for Monthly incomes of below \$7,500. After \$15,000 a divide begin to form, with higher incomes accessing higher loan amounts. No loans of above \$25,000 were issued for Incomes below \$7,500.

Conclusions¶

Salaries above \$20,000 were removed as there were very huge outlier in this range. BorrowerAPR has the most effect on the final LoanStatus outcome. There is a floor monthly income for loans above \$25,000. Higher income earners tended to be in the "Current" or "Complete" LoannStatus.
